In [31]:
def loaddata(URL, col_names):
    return pd.read_csv(URL, names=col_names, na_values="?")

def fill_na(data, strategy='mean'):
    columns = data.columns
    imp = Imputer(missing_values='NaN', strategy=strategy, axis=0)
    imp.fit(data)
    data = imp.transform(data)
    data = pd.DataFrame(data=data, columns=columns)
    return data
In [40]:
def train_svm(data, target, costs, gammas, n_jobs=4):
    parameters = [{'kernel': ['rbf'], 'C': costs, 'gamma': gammas},
                 {'kernel': ['linear'], 'C': costs}]
    svr = svm.SVC()
    grid = GridSearchCV(svr, parameters, cv = 10, n_jobs=n_jobs)

    bef = time()
    grid.fit(data, target)
    print "Best Params: ", grid.best_params_
    print "Best Score: ", grid.best_score_
    print 'Total time elapsed: %f minutes' % ((time() - bef) / 60)
    return grid
In [123]:
def train_randomforests_cv(data, target, n_jobs=4):
    param_grid = {'n_estimators': [10, 100, 1000, 10000]}

    cv = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=10, test_size=0.10)

    grid = GridSearchCV(RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=n_jobs), param_grid=param_grid, cv=10, verbose=1, n_jobs=n_jobs)
    bef = time()
    grid.fit(data, target)
    print "Best Params: ", grid.best_params_
    print "Best Score: ", grid.best_score_
    return grid

def train_randomforests_oob(data, target, n_jobs=4):
    param_grid = {'n_estimators': [10, 100, 1000, 10000]}
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=n_jobs, verbose=1, oob_score=True)
    oob_scores = []
    best_score = 0
    best_grid = None
    bef = time()
    for g in ParameterGrid(param_grid):
        clf.set_params(**g)
        clf.fit(data,target)
        oob_scores += [clf.oob_score_]
        if clf.oob_score_ > best_score:
            best_grid = g
            best_score = clf.oob_score_

    print "Best OOB: %0.5f" % best_score 
    print "Best Params:", best_grid
    print 'Total time elapsed: %f minutes' % ((time() - bef) / 60)
    return oob_scores

def get_feature_importance(data, target, n_trees, n_jobs=4):
    clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_jobs=n_jobs, verbose=1, n_estimators=n_trees, oob_score=True)
    clf.fit(data, target)
    return clf

def plot_svm_linear(grid, costs, gammas):
    plt.clf()
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (20,15)
    plt.plot(range(len(costs)), grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'][-len(costs):], '-bo', alpha=0.5)
    plt.xticks(range(len(costs)), np.round(costs, decimals=3))
    plt.xlabel("Cost", fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel("Score", fontsize=20)
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=15)
    plt.title("SVM Linear-Kernel", fontsize=25)
    plt.show()
    
def plot_svm_rbf(grid, costs, gammas):
    plt.clf()
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (20,15)
    for i in xrange(len(gammas)):
        points = [grid.cv_results_['mean_test_score'][len(gammas)*ind + i] for ind in xrange(len(costs))]
        if i == np.int(np.argwhere(np.array(gammas) == grid.best_params_['gamma'])):
            plt.plot(range(len(costs)), points, '-ko', alpha=0.5)
        else:
            plt.plot(range(len(costs)), points, alpha=0.5)
    plt.xticks(range(len(costs)), np.round(costs, decimals=3))

    plt_legend = plt.legend(np.round(gammas, decimals=3), title='gamma value', fontsize=15)
    plt_legend.get_title().set_fontsize('15')

    plt.xlabel("Cost", fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel("Score", fontsize=20)
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=15)
    plt.title("SVM RBF-Kernel", fontsize=25)
    plt.show()
    
def plot_randomforests(values, n_trees, title):
    plt.clf()
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (20,15)
    plt.plot(range(len(n_trees)), values, '-bo', alpha=0.8)
    plt.xticks(range(len(n_trees)), n_trees)
    plt.xlabel("n_trees", fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel("Score", fontsize=20)
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=15)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=25)
    plt.show()

def plot_oob_vs_cv(values1, values2, n_trees, title, legend):
    plt.clf()
    plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = (20,15)
    plt.plot(range(len(n_trees)), values1, '-bo', range(len(n_trees)), values2, '-ro', alpha=0.8)
    plt.xticks(range(len(n_trees)), n_trees)
    plt.xlabel("n_trees", fontsize=20)
    plt.ylabel("Score", fontsize=20)
    plt.tick_params(axis='both', which='major', labelsize=15)
    plt.title(title, fontsize=25)
    plt_legend = plt.legend(legend, fontsize=15)
    plt_legend.get_title().set_fontsize('15')
    plt.show()

                 "MarginalAdhesion", "SingleEpithelialCellSize", "BareNuclei", "BlandChromatin",
                 "NormalNucleoli", "Mitoses", "Class"]

we can see that the score actually dropped after handling the NAs, indicating that our handling wasn't proper. Probably the method we used "mean" is not the best here. Let's take a look on the 'BareNuclei' Column:

In [44]:
breast_cancer.BareNuclei.unique()
Out[44]:
array([  1.        ,  10.        ,   2.        ,   4.        ,
         3.        ,   9.        ,   7.        ,   3.54465593,
         5.        ,   8.        ,   6.        ])

We can clearly see the column contains discrete values between 1 and 10 and the 3.5 is the mean we just added. We can interpret that 'BareNuclei' only takes discrete values and the decimal number we added messed up the column data. A more proper way would've been the 'mode' since we just take the most repeated entry from the column and won't introduce new values.

**Sequence One hot encoded**
In [63]:
def one_hot_encoding(data):
    """
    Transforms the dataframe into a one_hot_encoded dataframe.
    
    :param data: dataframe
    :return:     datframe with 300 more columns
    """
    letters = ["A", "C", "D", "E", "F", "G", "H", "I", "K", "L", "M", "N", "P", "Q", "R", "S", "T", "V", "W", "Y"]
    col_names = []
    seq_len = 15
    # generating the column names "0_A", "1_A" .... for evey position of the 15
    for index in range(seq_len):
        col_names += [str(idx) + "_" + letter for idx, letter in zip([index]*20, letters)]

    # adding those columns to the dataframe with default value 0
    data = data.join(pd.DataFrame([[0]*seq_len*20], index=data.index, columns=col_names))
    # iterating over the rows and fixing the column values
    for i in xrange(len(data)):
        seq = data.loc[i, 'Seq']
        for index in xrange(len(seq)):
            data.loc[i, str(index) + "_" + seq[index]] = 1
    return data

sequence = loaddata('Sequences_train.csv', ['Seq', 'Class'])
